</P>
<P>
BUSH SIGNS CHILD NUTRITION MEASURE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Bush signed legislation that will require all states to use 
competitive bidding to buy food and formula for poor women, children and 
infants. Bush said the 28 states that already use competitive bidding in the 
Women's, Infants' and Children's program have saved $300 million this year and 
have been able to serve 500,000 more people. Bush signed the Child Nutrition 
and WIC Reauthorization Act on Air Force One while flying to Dallas for a 
speech. The measure "will save an additional $40 million and allow 68,000 more 
needy pregnant women, infants and children to participate in WIC," Bush said in 
a statement. Bush said he is "firmly committed to helping nutritionally 
deficient children obtain improved nourishment that will give them a better 
start in life." 
</P>
