<HEADLINE>
<P>
HARD-WORKING HEAVY METAL FAN SPEAKS OUT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
From time to time the newspapers run articles about organizations that are 
trying to ban heavy metal music because they feel it is a bad influence on 
teen-agers. 
</P>
<P>
I am a hard-working student at Dana Hills High School who strives to get good 
grades. I also listen to heavy metal music. My parents had trouble adjusting to 
my interest in heavy metal, but I pointed out to them that I do, indeed, get 
good grades and that I was aware of their concerns. I made a deal with them 
that if I started doing poorly in school, then they could take my tapes from 
me. 
</P>
<P>
I am very lucky to have the parents I have. Many won't even give the music a 
chance, much less their children, and others form activist groups that focus on 
the negative side of heavy metal rather than looking at the positive. 
</P>
<P>
It seems that these parents don't remember that our ancestors fought a 
revolution to win the rights we have today. One of these is the freedom of 
speech -- and music is a form of speech. 
</P>
<P>
Admittedly, some heavy metal bands do cause problems and are nothing but 
trouble. But there are a lot of other metal groups that do not. Many parents 
mistakenly feel that rock bands with long-haired singers and loud voices are 
bad, but they should take the time to listen to the music and see for 
themselves that it is not. 
</P>
<P>
BRIAN UNDERWOOD 
</P>
<P>
Laguna Niguel 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
